# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: server-side-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] A **dynamic web page** is a web page constructed at runtime (during software execution), as opposed to a *static web page*, delivered as it is stored.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] A **server-side dynamic web page** is a web page whose construction is controlled by an application server processing server-side scripts.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] In server-side scripting, parameters determine how the assembly of every new web page proceeds, and including the setting up of more client-side processing.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] A **client-side dynamic web page** processes the web page using JavaScript running in the browser as it loads.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] JavaScript can interact with the page via Document Object Model (DOM), to query page state and modify it.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Even though a web page can be dynamic on the client-side, it can still be hosted on a static hosting service such as GitHub Pages or Amazon S3 as long as there is not any server-side code included.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] A dynamic web page is then reloaded by the user or by a computer program to change some variable content.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The updating information could come from the server, or from changes made to that page's DOM.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] This may or may not truncate the browsing history or create a saved version to go back to, but a *dynamic web page update* using AJAX technologies will neither create a page to go back to, nor truncate the web browsing history forward of the displayed page.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Using AJAX, the end user gets one dynamic page managed as a single page in the web browser while the actual web content rendered on that page can vary.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The AJAX engine sits only on the browser requesting parts of its DOM, *the* DOM, for its client, from an application server.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] A particular application server could offer a standardized REST style interface to offer services to the web application.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] DHTML is the umbrella term for technologies and methods used to create web pages that are not static web pages, though it has fallen out of common use since the popularization of AJAX, a term which is now itself rarely used.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Client-side-scripting, server-side scripting, or a combination of these make for the dynamic web experience in a browser.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Classical hypertext navigation, with HTML or XHTML alone, provides "static" content, meaning that the user requests a web page and simply views the page and the information on that page.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] However, a web page can also provide a "live", "dynamic", or "interactive" user experience.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Content (text, images, form fields, etc.) on a web page can change, in response to different contexts or conditions.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Web pages that use client-side scripting must use presentation technology broadly called rich interfaced pages.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Client-side scripting languages like JavaScript or ActionScript, used for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) and Flash technologies respectively, are frequently used to orchestrate media types (sound, animations, changing text, etc.) of the presentation.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The scripting also allows use of remote scripting, a technique by which the DHTML page requests additional information from a server, using a hidden Frame, XMLHttpRequests, or a web service.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] It is also possible to use a web framework to create a web API, which the client, via the use of JavaScript, uses to obtain data and alter its appearance or behavior dynamically depending on the data.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Web pages that use server-side scripting are often created with the help of server-side languages such as PHP, Perl, ASP, JSP, ColdFusion and other languages.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] These server-side languages typically use the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) to produce *dynamic web pages*.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] These kinds of pages can also use, on the client-side, the first kind (DHTML, etc.).
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] It is difficult to be precise about "dynamic web page beginnings" or chronology because the precise concept makes sense only after the "widespread development of web pages".
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] HTTP has existed since 1989, HTML, publicly standardized since 1996.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The web browser's rise in popularity started with Mosaic in 1993.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Between 1995 and 1996, multiple dynamic web products were introduced to the market, including Coldfusion, WebObjects, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The introduction of JavaScript (then known as LiveScript) enabled the production of client-side dynamic web pages, with JavaScript code executed in the client's browser.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The letter "J" in the term AJAX originally indicated the use of JavaScript, as well as XML.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] With the rise of server side JavaScript processing, for example, Node.js, originally developed in 2009, JavaScript is also used to dynamically create pages on the server that are sent fully formed to clients.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] MediaWiki, the content management system that powers Wikipedia, is an example for an originally server-side dynamic web page, interacted with through form submissions and URL parameters.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] A program running on a web server is used to generate the web content on various web pages, manage user sessions, and control workflow.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Server responses may be determined by such conditions as data in a posted HTML form, parameters in the URL, the type of browser being used, the passage of time, or a database or server state.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Such web pages are often created with the help of server-side languages such as ASP, ColdFusion, Java, JavaScript, Perl, PHP, Ruby, Python, and other languages, by a **support server** that can run on the same hardware as the web server.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] These server-side languages often use the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) to produce dynamic web pages.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Two notable exceptions are ASP.NET, and JSP, which reuse CGI concepts in their APIs but actually dispatch all web requests into a shared virtual machine.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The server-side languages are used to embed tags or markers within the source file of the web page on the web server.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] When a user on a client computer requests that web page, the web server interprets these tags or markers to perform actions on the server.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] For example, the server may be instructed to insert information from a database or information such as the current date.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Dynamic web pages are often cached when there are few or no changes expected and the page is anticipated to receive considerable amount of web traffic that would wastefully strain the server and slow down page loading if it had to generate the pages on the fly for each request.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Client-side scripting is changing interface behaviors within a specific web page in response to input device actions, or at specified timing events.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] In this case, the dynamic behavior occurs within the presentation.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The client-side content is generated on the user's local computer system.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Such web pages use presentation technology called rich interfaced pages.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Client-side scripting also allows the use of remote scripting, a technique by which the DHTML page requests additional information from a server, using a hidden frame, XMLHttpRequests, or a Web service.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The first public use of JavaScript was in 1995, when the language was implemented in Netscape Navigator 2, standardized as ECMAScript two years later.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The client-side content is generated on the client's computer.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The web browser retrieves a page from the server, then processes the code embedded in the page (typically written in JavaScript) and displays the retrieved page's content to the user.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] All of the client and server components that collectively build a dynamic web page are called a web application.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Web applications manage user interactions, state, security, and performance.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Ajax uses a combination of both client-side scripting and server-side requests.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] It is a web application development technique for dynamically interchanging content, and it sends requests to the server for data in order to do so.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] The server returns the requested data which is then processed by a client-side script.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] This technique can reduce server load time because the client does not request the entire webpage to be regenerated by the server's language parser; only the content that will change is transmitted.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] Google Maps is an example of a web application that uses Ajax techniques.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] A web client, such as a web browser, can act as its own server, accessing data from many different servers, such as Gopher, FTP, NNTP (Usenet) and HTTP, to build a page.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] HTTP supports uploading documents from the client back to the server.
[src:server-side-rendering/dynamic-web-page] There are several HTTP methods for doing this.
[src:server-side-rendering/hydration-web-development] Frameworks that use hydration include Next.js and Nuxt.
[src:server-side-rendering/hydration-web-development] React v16.0 introduced a "hydrate" function, which hydrates an element, in its API.
[src:server-side-rendering/hydration-web-development] In *progressive rehydration*, individual pieces of a server-rendered application are “booted up” over time, rather than the current common approach of initializing the entire application at once.
[src:server-side-rendering/hydration-web-development] This can help reduce the amount of JavaScript required to make pages interactive, since client-side upgrading of low priority parts of the page can be deferred to prevent blocking the main thread.
[src:server-side-rendering/hydration-web-development] One framework that supports partial rehydration is Elder.js, which is based on Svelte.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] This strategy involves separating the presentation semantics from the content, with presentation being implemented in one or more optional layers, activated based on aspects of the browser or Internet connection of the client.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] In practice, this means serving content through HTML, the "lowest common denominator" of web standards, and applying styling and animation through CSS to the technically possible extent, then applying further enhancements through JavaScript.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Deprecated Adobe Flash could be thought of as having shared the final spot with JavaScript while it was widely in use.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Since web browsers can load site features to the extent supported rather than failing to load the entire site due to one error or missing feature in JavaScript, a progressively enhancing site is more stable and backwards compatible.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] "Progressive enhancement" was coined by Steven Champeon and Nick Finck at the SXSW Interactive conference on March 11, 2003, in Austin, and through a series of articles for Webmonkey which were published between March and June 2003.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Specific Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) techniques pertaining to flexibility of the page layout accommodating different screen resolutions is the concept associated with the responsive web design approach.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] In 2012, net Magazine chose Progressive Enhancement as #1 on its list of Top Web Design Trends for 2012 (responsive design was #2).
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Google has encouraged the adoption of progressive enhancement to help "our systems (and a wider range of browsers) see usable content and basic functionality when certain web design features are not yet supported".
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] The strategy is an evolution of a previous web design strategy known as graceful degradation, wherein Web pages were designed for the latest browsers first, but then made to work well in older versions of browser software.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Graceful degradation aims to allow a page to "degrade" – to remain presentable and accessible even if certain technologies expected by the design are absent.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] In progressive enhancement the strategy is deliberately reversed: The web content is created with a markup document, geared towards the lowest common denominator of browser software functionality.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] If content is to be revealed interactively through JavaScript, such as a collapsible navigation menu, the HTML markup reveals all the content by default and JavaScript itself hides some of the content.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] The developer adds all desired functionality to the presentation and behavior of the page, using modern CSS, Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG), or JavaScript.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] The progressive enhancement approach is derived from Champeon's early experience (c.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] 1993–1994) with Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML), predating HTML and other Web presentation languages.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Writing content with semantic markup and considering the presentation of the content separately, rather than being embedded in the markup itself, is a concept referred to as the rule of *separation of presentation and content*.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Champeon expressed a hope that, since web browsers provide a default presentation style for HTML content, this would result in websites with their content written as semantic HTML, leaving presentation choice to the web browser.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] However, the needs of web designers led to the HTML standard being extended with hardcoded features that allowed HTML content to prescribe specific styles, and taking away this option from consumers and their web browsers.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] These features forced publishers to choose between adopting a new disruptive technologies or allowing content to remain accessible to audiences that used other browsers, a dilemma between design and compatibility.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] During the 1990s, an increasing number of websites would not work in anything but the latest versions of popular browsers.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] This trend reversed after the 1990s, once CSS was widely supported, through grassroots educational efforts (from Eric Costello, Owen Briggs, Dave Shea, and others) showing Web designers how to use CSS for layout purposes.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Additionally, the sparse markup principle makes it easier for tools that read content aloud to find that content.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] It is unclear as to how well progressive enhancement sites work with older tools designed to deal with table layouts, "tag soup", and the like.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] The client is able to select which parts of a page to download beyond basic HTML (e.g. styling, images, etc.), and can opt only to download parts necessary for desired usage to speed up loading and reduce bandwidth and power consumption.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] For example, a client may choose to only download basic HTML, without loading style sheets, scripts, and media (e.g. images), due to low internet speeds caused by geographical location, poor cellular signal, or throttled speed due to exhausted high-speed data plan.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] This also reduces bandwidth consumption on the server side.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] In comparison, pages whose initial content is loaded through AJAX require the client to inefficiently run JavaScript to download and view page content, rather than downloading the content immediately.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Improved results with respect to search engine optimization (SEO) is another side effect of a progressive enhancement-based Web design strategy.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Because the basic content is always accessible to search engine spiders, pages built with progressive enhancement methods avoid problems that may hinder search engine indexing, whereas having to render the basic page content through JavaScript execution would make crawling slow and inefficient.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Some skeptics, such as Garret Dimon, have expressed their concern that progressive enhancement is not workable in situations that rely heavily on JavaScript to achieve certain user interface presentations or behaviors.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Laurie Gray (Information Architect at KnowledgeStorm) countered with the point that informational pages should be coded using progressive enhancement in order to be indexed by search engine spiders.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Geoff Stearns (author of SWFObject, a popular Flash application) argued that Flash-heavy pages should be coded using progressive enhancement.
[src:server-side-rendering/progressive-enhancement] Designers Douglas Bowman and Bob Stein expressed doubts concerning the principle of the separation of content and presentation in absolute terms, pushing instead for a realistic recognition that the two are inextricably linked.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:server-side-rendering/server-side-scripting] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] A **web template system** in web publishing allows web designers and developers to work with *web templates* to automatically generate custom web pages, such as the results from a search.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] This reuses static web page elements while defining dynamic elements based on web request parameters.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Web templates support static content, providing basic structure and appearance.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Developers can implement templates from content management systems, web application frameworks, and HTML editors.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] The template and content resources are processed and combined by the template engine to mass-produce web documents, each with a similar visual format.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, web documents include any of various output formats for transmission over the web via HTTP, HTTPS, or another Internet protocol.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] A template processor (also known as a template engine or template parser) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] The language that the templates are written in is known as a template language or templating language.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] With the model typically held in a relational database, the remaining components of the MVC architecture are the control and view.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] In the simplest of systems these two are not separated.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] However, adapting the separation of concerns principle one can completely decouple the relationships.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] A web browser and web server are a client–server architecture.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Sites often also use a web cache to improve performance.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] In many implementations, template files contain variables or placeholders that are replaced with data supplied by an application when the page is generated.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] The source code of the template engine can be proprietary or open source.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Many template systems are a component of a larger programming platform or framework.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] They are referred to as the "platform's template system".
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Some template systems have the option of substituting a different template language or engine.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Programming languages such as Perl, Ruby, C, and Java support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] JavaServer Pages (JSP), PHP, and Active Server Pages (ASP with VBScript, JScript or other languages) are examples, themselves, of web template engines.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] These technologies are typically used in server-side templating systems, but could be adapted for use on an "edge-side" proxy or for static page generation.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Static site generators are engines that use flat text input files like markdown and asciidoc to generate a static web page.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Examples of this include Jekyll (Liquid, Ruby), Hugo (Go templates), and Pelican (Jinja2, Python).
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Some hosted website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, provide template-based systems that allow users to create static and dynamic web pages through graphical user interfaces rather than traditional programming.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] HTML editors often use web template systems to produce only static web pages.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] These can be viewed as a ready-made web design, used to mass-produce "cookie-cutter" websites for rapid deployment.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] They also commonly include themes in place of CSS styles.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] In general, the template language is used only with the editor's software.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] FrontPage and Dreamweaver were once the most popular editors with template sub-systems.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] A Flash web template uses Macromedia Flash to create visually interactive sites.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Many *server-side template systems* have an option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existent software adapted for this task.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for the web use, running on CGI.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, started with SSI.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Technically, the methodology of embedding programming languages within HTML (or XML, etc.), used in many "server-side included script languages" are also templates.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] All of them are Embedded complex languages.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] There are also preprocessors used as server-side template engines.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] As for edge-side template and inclusion systems, "edge-side" refers to web servers that reside in the space between the client (browser) and the originating server.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] They are often referred to as "reverse-proxy" servers.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] These servers are generally tasked with reducing the load and traffic on originating servers by caching content such as images and page fragments, and delivering this to the browser in an efficient manner.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Basic Edge Side Includes (ESI) is an SSI-like language.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] ESI has been implemented for content delivery networks.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] The ESI template language may also be implemented in web browsers using JavaScript and Ajax, or via a browser "plug-in".
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] Many web browsers can apply an XSLT stylesheet to XML data that transforms the data into an XHTML document, thereby providing template functionality in the browser itself.
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] The most simple form is transclusions (HTML frames).
[src:server-side-rendering/web-template-system] In other cases dynamic web pages are needed.
